properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for the Thomson River.

Moderate to major flooding likely across East Gippsland from overnight Sunday into Monday.

  • A low pressure system tracking into eastern Bass Strait is bringing moderate to heavy and at times intense rainfall to East Gippsland and eastern parts of West and South Gippsland during Sunday and Monday morning.
  • Catchments across Gippsland are relatively wet. In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Sunday widespread rainfall totals of 30-80 mm have been recorded across Gippsland. Higher totals of up to 120 mm have been recorded across the Bemm and Cann catchments.
  • During the remainder of Sunday and Monday rainfall totals of 20-80 mm are forecast for parts of West,and East Gippsland with isolated totals of up to 100 mm and higher possible on the slopes east of Lakes Entrance with storms.
  • Moderate to major flooding likely across East Gippsland from overnight Sunday into Monday. Minor flooding possible across parts of West Gippsland and generalised flooding possible in the eastern parts of SouthGippsland from Sunday.
  • This Advice replaces the Advice issued Saturday at 12.45pm.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 04/04/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Community Information
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for water quality at Barwon Heads. 

  • High levels of Blue Green Algae have been detected in the Lake Connewarre and the lower reaches of the Barwon River near Barwon Heads.
  • The algal bloom is expected to remain until there is significant rainfall to flush the lake or cooler conditions slow the algae. 
  • Warnings signs have been installed at various locations, people should avoid direct contact with the water until the algal bloom disperses. 
  • The Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning (DELWP) /Barwon Coast Committee of Management and Parks Victoria will continue monitoring the Barwon River near Barwon Heads and Lake Connewarre until the bloom disperses and will advise when the river and lake is safe for use again.
You should avoid direct contact with affected water in Lake Connewarre and the lower reaches of the Barwon River.

Do not swim in affected areas or use water for cooking, drinking, washing or showering. Boiling the water will not make it safe. 
What you should do:
  • Visit https://www.health.vic.gov.au/water/health-effects-of-blue-green-algae for more information. 
  • Observe information signs posted at various locations. 

Protect your health:
  • Direct contact with water affected by blue green algae can cause skin irritation, sore eyes, ears and nose. If swallowed it can cause cramps, nausea and vomiting. 
  • If you do come into contact with affected water, wash your skin immediately in clean cool water. 
  • Boiling affected water does not make it safe to drink. Boiling water bursts the blue green algae cells and releases toxins into the water making it more likely that you will experience symptoms. 
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctor or Nurse-On-Call on 1300 60 60 24.

Protect your pets:
  • Pet owners should prevent pets from drinking or having direct contact with contaminated water. 
Impacts in your area:
  • The water is green as a result of the algae bloom.

Boating and fishing:
  • Recreational activities in the river should be avoided, which includes swimming and boating.
  • Any fish harvested from the river and lake must have the gills and guts removed prior to cooking. 
  • People should not eat whole fish, or shellfish or crustaceans collected from Lake Connewarre or the Barwon River.
  • The type of algae affecting Lake Connewarre and the Barwon River produces toxins that can concentrate in shellfish and crustaceans and accumulate in the liver and internal organs of fish. Ingesting BGA toxins can lead to serious illness.

This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 14/04/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Information about blue green algae:
  • For information on blue green algae visit: https://www.health.vic.gov.au/water/blue-green-algae-cyanobacteria.
  • For information on blue green algae and stock visit: https://agriculture.vic.gov.au/farm-management/water/blue-green-algae-in-water/managing-bluegreen-algae-in-farm-water-supplies
  • For information on blue green algae and irrigation visit: https://agriculture.vic.gov.au/farm-management/water/blue-green-algae-in-water/bluegreen-algae-and-irrigation-water

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Mitchell River downstream of Glenaladale.

The Mitchell River at Bairnsdale is currently at 3.11 metres and rising. The Mitchell River at Bairnsdale is expected to exceed the minor flood level (4.00 m) late Sunday afternoon. 

The river level is likely to reach the moderate flood level (5.50 m) Monday morning. Further rises are possible.
Prepare to take actions to protect your life and property, and consider moving to higher ground.


What you should do:

  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings.

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 

If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:  
Low-lying areas near the waterway may become flooded 

Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides – be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 03/04/2022 10:30 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.  
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch and Act message is being issued for Bemm River.

It is now time for Bemm River residents to enact their flood plan due to the potential impacts of the coming flood water.  

Road access is expected to be cut at Sydenham Inlet Road at Bemm River later this afternoon into Sunday night. Other access routes may also be affected.

During the remainder of Sunday rainfall totals of 40-80 mm are forecast for the Bemm, Cann and Genoa River catchments.
You may become isolated, with no access in or out of your home. Ensure you have prepared for this event or consider leaving now. 

Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications if you leave. 
What you should do: 

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 

If you are travelling: 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 

Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.  
  • Further main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 03/04/2022 09:30 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Avon River.

Minor flooding is possible along the Avon River at Stratford on Sunday night. Strong rises have been observed along the Avon River and Freestone Creek.

Up to 30 mm was observed across the Avon River catchment in the 24 hrs to 9:00 am Sunday. Since 9:00am, a further 5-25 mm has been recorded across the catchment.

For the remainder of Sunday, rainfall totals up to 20 mm are forecast in the lower part of the catchment.  

The Avon River at Stratford is currently at 3.87 metres and rising. The Avon River at Stratford may reach the minor flood level (4.50m) Sunday night.

This Advice message replaces the Flood Watch message issued Sunday 3 April at 12:03PM.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

Major Flooding may develop in the Buchan River from early Monday morning.

Major flooding may develop in the Buchan River and in the lower Snowy River from early Monday morning. Moderate flooding is likely to develop in the Buchan River and in the lower Snowy River from Sunday night. Minor flooding is already occurring at Buchan. 

Heavy rain was recorded overnight in the Snowy River catchment. Since 9:00 am Sunday, additional rainfall totals of up to 30 mm were recorded across the lower parts of the catchment. 

During the remainder of Sunday rainfall totals of 30-50 mm are forecast for the lower Snowy River catchment. Rainfall totals of 5-15 mm are forecast for the upper Snowy River catchment. Higher isolated totals are possible from embedded thunderstorms.

A severe weather warning for heavy rainfall is current for East Gippsland. 

The Buchan River at Buchan is currently at 3.04 metres and rising, with minor flooding. It is expected to exceed the moderate flood level (3.50 m) Sunday night and may reach the major flood level (4.00 m) early Monday morning. Further rises are possible. 

Move stock and machinery to higher ground. Act now - take actions to protect your life and property.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Tambo and Nicholson River. 

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT D/S RAMROD CREEK, MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM EARLY MONDAY MORNING Minor flooding is occurring at D/S Ramrod Creek and moderate flooding is possible from early Monday morning. River rises are also being observed along the Nicholson River. Since 9:00 am Sunday rainfall totals of 45 mm have been observed in the lower reaches of the catchment. Rainfall is expected to ease from early Monday morning across the catchment.

Tambo River:Moderate flooding may occur along the Tambo River.The Tambo River D/S Ramrod Creek is currently at 4.67 metres (minor flooding) and rising. The Tambo River D/S Ramrod Creek may reach the moderate flood level (6.90 m) early Monday morning.
Nicholson River:River rises are expected along the Nicholson River during overnight Sunday into Monday.

Some low-lying areas of Sarsfield may become isolated due to flood water, similar to the 2021 floods. And it is predicted the boat ramp and carpark will be affected. 

This Watch and Act message replaces the Advice issued for Nicholson River at 12:36PM Sunday 3 April 2022. 
Act now - prepare to take action to protect your life and property, and to move to higher ground.
What you should do:
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Owners should provide lengthening to mooring lines of boats located at jetties throughout the Tambo and Nicholson River watercourse.

  • Campers and Caravans near the river should prepare now and consider relocating before the water levels rise.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one. Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 

If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:

  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

  • Flooding is likely to occur in low lying areas.
  • Roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.

Tambo River:  
  • Swan Reach - Mossiface Road at Wharf Corner (known as Clancey's Corner) is likely to be cut off by flood waters.
  • The Evans Track bridge (Ramrod Bridge) will be submerged with water spilling across the rural land of the river flats below Bruthen.
Nicholson River:
  • The boat ramp and carpark at Nicholson on the Nicholson River is likely to be flooded.
  • Low lying areas around Sarsfield may become isolated by flood waters
  • 'Boss Swamp' may rise and overtop the Princes Highway at Nicholson.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 04/04/2022 09:30 am or as the situation changes.

  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for the South Gippsland Rivers.

Moderate to major flooding likely across East Gippsland from overnight Sunday into Monday.

  • A low pressure system tracking into eastern Bass Strait is bringing moderate to heavy and at times intense rainfall to East Gippsland and eastern parts of West and South Gippsland during Sunday and Monday morning.
  • Catchments across Gippsland are relatively wet. In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Sunday widespread rainfall totals of 30-80 mm have been recorded across Gippsland. Higher totals of up to 120 mm have been recorded across the Bemm and Cann catchments.
  • During the remainder of Sunday and Monday rainfall totals of 20-80 mm are forecast for parts of West and East Gippsland with isolated totals of up to 100 mm and higher possible on the slopes east of Lakes Entrance with storms.
  • Moderate to major flooding likely across East Gippsland from overnight Sunday into Monday. Minor flooding possible across parts of West Gippsland and generalised flooding possible in the eastern parts of South Gippsland from Sunday.
  • This Advice replaces the advice issued at 12.45pm. 
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded. 
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded. 
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 04/04/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
properties.text:
ADVICE - RIVERINE FLOOD - Stay Informed
Incident Location: South Gippsland Rivers
Issue Date: Sunday 03 April 2022, 12:14 pm
Next Update: Monday 04 April 2022, 01:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/20515/moreinfo

This Flood Watch is being issued for the South Gippsland Rivers.

Moderate to major flooding likely across East Gippsland from overnight Sunday into Monday.

- A low pressure system tracking into eastern Bass Strait is bringing moderate to heavy and at times intense rainfall to East Gippsland and eastern parts of West and South Gippsland during Sunday and Monday morning.
- Catchments across Gippsland are relatively wet. In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Sunday widespread rainfall totals of 30-80 mm have been recorded across Gippsland. Higher totals of up to 120 mm have been recorded across the Bemm and Cann catchments.
- During the remainder of Sunday and Monday rainfall totals of 20-80 mm are forecast for parts of West and East Gippsland with isolated totals of up to 100 mm and higher possible on the slopes east of Lakes Entrance with storms.
- Moderate to major flooding likely across East Gippsland from overnight Sunday into Monday. Minor flooding possible across parts of West Gippsland and generalised flooding possible in the eastern parts of South Gippsland from Sunday. 
- This Advice replaces the advice issued at 12.45pm. 



Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
